<br>
A fair percentage of the fly fishing guides use drift boats here, maybe 20%. The rest of them use powered jon boats. A long slender boat with a narrow frame. The boat is best for making its way across gravel beds and through rocks. Canoes work well on &quot;low&quot; water but can be a bit much when the water approaches 4000 cfs. Remember that our water can get to 24,000 cfs. You probably wouldn't want to be in a canoe on that type of water. <br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=blackghost@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Black Ghost</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#000000>(4/15/03 9:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=59.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drift Boats</span><hr size=1> Nope I wouldn't, even 30 years ago when I was a bigger risk taker.<br>
