<br>
In my humble opinion Heres the Gig with boats and why one should use a John Boat with a motor.  <br>
<br>
Lets start with the Shad Kill.  Motor up to the 100yard mark and Drift.  Catch fish fight down to state park and release fish.  Motor back up.  Make another Drift, Catch Fish Release somewhere down stream.  Repeat....Repeat.<br>
<br>
Pass Drift boat 4 or 5 times while he is motoring back up to the line to make his second pass.  <br>
<br>
Now lets figure in a 4-6-or 8 unit rise....The drift boat is great for a steady clean two units of water.  Throw in more water and a dirty rise and the drift boat can't stay in front of it or even ride it. Heck a dirft boat can't even get up stream to find clean water .... even if it has a 15 hp motor a drift boat would take an hour to get where a John Boat w'a 15hp could get to in 15 minutes.<br>
<br>
Steve I'm not picking on you.  Drift boats have their place and I have never been in one but I really don't think they are the right tool to do the Job on the White River in any and all conditions that it can throw at you. <br>
<br>
Yes.... an inflatable pontoon or a drift boat can be a lot of fun and will get one down the river.  But it's pretty hard to get back up in low or hi water or for that matter in any water motor or not.  <br>
<br>
I don't have a clue about the little red or the beaver.  I do know they work on the Taneycomo....and the norfork on hi-water.  <br>
<br>
Besides it's hard to push fish with a drift boat ;}<br>
<br>
<br>
